/** Attribute names and values. While the XML spec doesn't require
ant,     *  preserving the order ( AFAIK ), some ant tests do rely on the
ant,     *  exact order. The following code is copied from AttributeImpl.
ant,     *  We could also just use SAX2 Attributes and convert to SAX1 ( DOM
ant,     *  attribute Nodes can also be stored in SAX2 Attributes )
ant,     *  XXX under JDK 1.4 you can just use a LinkedHashMap for this purpose -jglick
ant,     * The only exception to this order is the treatment of
ant,     * refid. A number of datatypes check if refid is set
ant,     * when other attributes are set. This check will not
ant,     * work if the build script has the other attribute before
ant,     * the "refid" attribute, so now (ANT 1.7) the refid
ant,     * attribute will be processed first.
ant,     */

Will be an absolute path if the given URI is absolute.

ant, * ant, *

Prior to Java 1.4, ant, * swallows '%' that are not followed by two characters.

ant, * ant, * See dt-sysid ant, * which makes some mention of how ant, * characters not supported by URI Reference syntax should be escaped. ant, * ant, * @param uri the URI designating a file in the local filesystem. ant, * @return the local file system path for the file. ant, * @throws IllegalArgumentException if the URI is malformed or not a legal file: URL ant, * @since Ant 1.6 ant, */

name: CommonsLoggingListener.java
comment_text:
/**
ant, * Jakarta Commons Logging listener.
ant, * Note: do not use the SimpleLog as your logger implementation as it
ant, * causes an infinite loop since it writes to System.err, which Ant traps
ant, * and reroutes to the logger/listener layer.
ant, *
ant, * The following names are used for the log:
ant, *  org.apache.tools.ant.Project.PROJECT_NAME  - for project events
ant, *  org.apache.tools.ant.Target.TARGET_NAME - for target events
ant, *  TASK_CLASS_NAME.TARGET_NAME - for events in individual targets.
ant, *
ant, * In all target and project names we replace "." and " " with "-".
ant, *
ant, * TODO: we should use the advanced context logging features ( and expose them
ant, * in c-l first :-)
ant, * TODO: this is _very_ inefficient. Switching the out and tracking the logs
ant, * can be optimized a lot - but may require few more changes to the core.
ant, *
ant, * @author Erik Hatcher
ant, * @since Ant 1.5
ant, */

comment_text:
/* for historical and performance reasons we have to do
ant,	       things in a rather complex way.
ant,	    
ant,	       (1) Move is optimized to move directories if a fileset
ant,	       has been included completely, therefore FileSets need a
ant,	       special treatment.  This is also required to support
ant,	       the failOnError semantice (skip filesets with broken
ant,	       basedir but handle the remaining collections).
ant,
ant,	       (2) We carry around a few protected methods that work
ant,	       on basedirs and arrays of names.  To optimize stuff, all
ant,	       resources with the same basedir get collected in
ant,	       separate lists and then each list is handled in one go.
ant,	    */

name: BlockSort.java
comment_text:
/*
ant,     * 2012-05-20 Stefan Bodewig:
ant,     *
ant,     * This class seems to mix several revisions of libbzip2's code.
ant,     * The mainSort function and those used by it look closer to the
ant,     * 0.9.5 version but show some variations introduced later.  At
ant,     * the same time the logic of Compress 1.4 to randomize the block
ant,     * on bad input has been dropped after libbzip2 0.9.0 and replaced
ant,     * by a fallback sorting algorithm.
ant,     *
ant,     * I've added the fallbackSort function of 1.0.6 and tried to
ant,     * integrate it with the existing code without touching too much.
ant,     * I've also removed the now unused randomization code.
ant,     */

name: CBZip2OutputStream.java
comment_text:
/** ant, * An output stream that compresses into the BZip2 format (without the file ant, * header chars) into another stream. ant, ant, *

The compression requires large amounts of memory. Thus you ant, * should call the {@link #close() close()} method as soon as ant, * possible, to force CBZip2OutputStream to release the ant, * allocated memory.

ant, * ant, *

You can shrink the amount of allocated memory and maybe raise ant, * the compression speed by choosing a lower blocksize, which in turn ant, * may cause a lower compression ratio. You can avoid unnecessary ant, * memory allocation by avoiding using a blocksize which is bigger ant, * than the size of the input.

ant, * ant, *

You can compute the memory usage for compressing by the ant, * following formula:

ant, * 
ant, * 400k + (9 * blocksize).
ant, *
ant, * ant, *

To get the memory required for decompression by {@link ant, * CBZip2InputStream CBZip2InputStream} use

ant, * 
ant, * 65k + (5 * blocksize).
ant, *

400k4000k2065k

800k7600k4065k
900k8500k4565k
ant, * ant, *

For decompression CBZip2InputStream allocates less ant, * memory if the bzipped input is smaller than one block.

ant, * ant, *

Instances of this class are not threadsafe.

ant, * ant, *

ant, * TODO: Update to BZip2 1.0.1 ant, *

ant, * ant, */

comment_text:
/** 
ant, * Abstract component creation and configuration.
ant, *
ant, * TODO: Multiple ComponentHelpers can be registered in a project, either by an
ant, * embedding application or by taskdef-like tasks.
ant, *
ant, * After a ProjectComponentHelper is registered, it'll manage the construction and 
ant, * configuration of tasks/types/etc. It has full control over how the
ant, * component is created - and may provide runtime wrapping for components
ant, * not implementing the Task/DataType interfaces.
ant, * It works in close relation with TaskAdapter and RuntimeConfigurable
ant, * to handle delayed evaluation of tasks or custom attribute->task mapping.
ant, * If it returns a wrapper for Task, the wrapper is required to extend
ant, * TaskAdapter.
ant, *
ant, * The common 'Chain' pattern is used to construct
ant, * tasks, with the original behavior ( Class registry ) tried last, by the
ant, * default helper implementation.
ant, *
ant, * Note that 'delayed' construction of tasks is used.
ant, *
ant, * @author Costin Manolache
ant, */

ant,                 * characters go away and skip one argument forward.

ant,                 * to help or not, so we simply look for the equals sign.
ant,                 */

name: SampleResult.java
comment_text:
/*
jmeter,	 * TODO: error counting needs to be sorted out after 2.3 final.
jmeter,	 * At present the Statistical Sampler tracks errors separately
jmeter,	 * It would make sense to move the error count here, but this would
jmeter,	 * mean lots of changes.
jmeter,	 * It's also tricky maintaining the count - it can't just be incremented/decremented
jmeter,	 * when the success flag is set as this may be done multiple times.
jmeter,	 * The work-round for now is to do the work in the StatisticalSampleResult,
jmeter,	 * which overrides this method.
jmeter,	 * Note that some JMS samplers also create samples with > 1 sample count
jmeter,	 * Also the Transaction Controller probably needs to be changed to do
jmeter,	 * proper sample and error accounting.
jmeter,	 * The purpose of this work-round is to allow at least minimal support for
jmeter,	 * errors in remote statistical batch mode.
jmeter,	 * 
jmeter,	 */
